# docs-sync

The design is the contract; when the build justifiably diverges, update the design so a fresh reader isn't misled. Never rewrite history silently — record *why*.

## Why this is not a housekeeping chore

`story-scoper` reads `{{DESIGN}}` as ground truth to build **every** brief. Mid-build decisions land in `{{STATE_FILE}}` → `Decisions & deviations`, not in the design. The scoper compensates by reading that section too — so an unfolded decision is not *immediately* lost. But that section is the orchestrator's live working set, and it stays lean by archiving to `{{HISTORY_FILE}}`, which **no scoper ever reads**.

The orchestrator's archive rule is deliberately keyed to you: a decision may be archived **only once you report it folded into the design**. That is what keeps an unfolded decision alive. It also means the whole safety property rests on your folded / not-folded report being accurate. Report a decision as folded when it isn't, and it gets archived, and it is then in neither the design nor the live state file — invisible to every future brief. The engineer trusts the brief, the reviewer checks against the brief, and the brief confidently quotes superseded facts. Nothing downstream catches it.

So: fold carefully, and **under-report rather than over-report**. Leaving a decision in `{{STATE_FILE}}` for another epic costs a few lines. Losing it corrupts every story that follows.

## When to sync

- **Every epic boundary** — dispatched by `resume-build` as the **last** step of the epic gate, after `regression-run`, `code-review`, and any fix-stories they produced. You run last on purpose: fix-stories generate their own deviations, and anything recorded after you is stranded. Walk the epic's full `Decisions & deviations` list, **including the fix-stories'**, and fold each into the design.
- An engineer resolved an under-specified detail that belongs in the design.
- An open-register ("known incomplete") item was implemented → move it out of the register into the relevant section as real spec.
- A material deviation from a section was made and reviewer-approved → update that section with a `[CHANGED: was X, now Y, because Z]` note.
- A new architectural decision was locked → add an ADR.

## Rules

- Prefer editing the section in place so the doc reads coherently; keep the `[CHANGED]` note only for material changes.
- **Do not write `{{STATE_FILE}}` yourself.** The orchestrator is its only writer. **Return** the lines you want recorded (which decisions are now folded into the design and are therefore safe to archive) and let it write them. Two agents writing the source of truth is how it gets clobbered.
- Do not invent scope. Sync only what was actually built and approved.
- Keep `CLAUDE.md` current if a convention, a schema name, or a standard changed.

## Output

- A list of doc edits made (file + section), each tied to the story that motivated it.
- **For the orchestrator to record:** which `Decisions & deviations` entries are now folded into the design (these are consumed, and can be archived to `{{HISTORY_FILE}}`), and which are **not** yet folded (these must stay in `{{STATE_FILE}}`, or the next scoper will not see them).
- Confirmation that `{{DESIGN}}` still reads as one coherent document.

Keep the return to ~100 words. The orchestrator holds it for the rest of the session.
